    //DOM (DOCUMENT OBJECT MODEL)
    --Its a programming interface in web development that allows us to 
    interact and manipulate(change) the html documents.

    --When the webpage is loaded , the browser creates the DOM of the webpage.
    
    --When an html file is loaded into the brower, the javascript cannot understand 
    the html document directly.
    

    DOM : it is basically the representation of the same html document but in a tree-like structure composed
    of objects.

    HTML DOM : It allow javascript to access(to get) and modify all the elements in HTML Document.

Keypoints:
1.Structure: the DOM represents the structure of html document as tree; each node in a tree represents the element , an attribute, text
2.Manipulation: using js, you can interact with elements like buttons, headings, paragraphs.
3.Event handling:
4.W3C: world wide web cosortium

<html>
<head>
<body>  
â€¦content in a tree like structure

</body>
</<head>
</html>

In dom all html elements are defined objects
Property: value that you can set to the objects(like changing content of a html element)
Method: an action(like adding or deleting)

Methods of DO:
1.Getting element by id
2.Getting element by class: returns all the elements having the same class name, return in the form of a html collection object
3.Getting an element by tagname
4.Getting an element by query selector.



//CODE:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Document</title>
    <style>
        .a{
            color: red;
        }
        .b{
            color: navy;
        }
        .c{
            color: black;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1 id="a" class="b">Akshith</h1>
    <h1 class="b" id="b">Rishi</h1>
    <h1 class="b" id="c">Nithin</h1>
    <h1 class="b">Jayadeep</h1>
    <h1 class="c">Sreenath</h1>
    <h1 class="a">Hrushi</h1>
    <h1 class="a">Phani</h1>
    <h1 class="a">Badulla</h1>
    <h1 class="c">Sri</h1>

    <script>
        let x=document.getElementsByClassName('a');
        console.log(x);
    </script>
</body>
</html>












